==Structure== The ''honden'' on the grounds at Sumiyoshi Taisha has been designated as a [[National Treasures of Japan|national treasure]] on the grounds that it is the oldest example of this style of architecture. The four identical ''honden'' buildings that compose it are 4 ''ken'' wide and 2 ''ken'' deep and have an entrance under one of the [[gable]]s (a characteristic called {{nihongo|''[[tsumairi]]-zukuri''|妻入造}}. The roof is simple, doesn't curve upwards at the eaves and is decorated with purely ornamental poles called ''[[chigi (architecture)|chigi]]'' (vertical) and ''[[katsuogi]]'' (horizontal).<ref name="yahoo">[https://archive.is/20121209043808/http://100.yahoo.co.jp/detail/%E7%A5%9E%E7%A4%BE%E5%BB%BA%E7%AF%89/ Jinja Kenchiku], [[Shogakukan]] Nihon Daihyakka Zensho, accessed on November 29, 2009</ref> The building is surrounded by a fence called {{nihongo|[[tamagaki|mizugaki]]|瑞垣}}, in its turn surrounded by another called {{nihongo|''[[tamagaki]]''|玉垣}} (see image in the gallery).<ref name="jasu"/> There is no veranda, and a short stairway leads to the door.
The interior is divided in two sections, one at the front ({{nihongo|''gejin''|外陣}}) and one at the back ({{nihongo|''naijin''|内陣}}) with a single entrance at the front (see floor plan in the gallery).<ref name="jasu">JAANUS, [http://www.aisf.or.jp/~jaanus/deta/s/sumiyoshizukuri.htm Sumiyoshi-zukuri], accessed on December 1, 2009</ref> The structure is simple, but brightly colored: supporting pillars are painted in vermilion and walls in white.
This style is supposed to have its origin in old palace architecture<ref name="jasu"/> Another example of this style is Sumiyoshi Jinja, part of the [[Sumiyoshi Sanjin]] complex in [[Fukuoka Prefecture]].<ref name="jasu"/>
