[[Category:Pages without translation templates]] [[Category:Pages with valid en interwikis]] [[Category:pages with valid en interwikis 2]] <!--enwiki derived wikidata interwikis--> [[fr:Sumiyoshi-zukuri]] [[ja:住吉造]] [[ru:Сумиёси-дзукури]] [[zh:住吉造]]

{{Short description|Shinto architectural style}} {{italic title}} [[File:Sumiyoshi Taisha Hunatama Jinja1.jpg|thumb|200 px|Sumiyoshi Taisha's Funatama Jinja]] {{Nihongo|'''''Sumiyoshi-zukuri'''''|住吉造}} is an ancient Japanese [[Shinto shrine]] [[Shinto architecture|architectural style]] which takes its name from [[Sumiyoshi-taisha|Sumiyoshi Taisha]]'s ''[[honden]]'' in [[:en:Osaka|Osaka]]. As in the case of the ''[[taisha-zukuri]]'' and ''[[shinmei-zukuri]]'' styles, its birth predates the arrival of [[:en:Buddhism in Japan|Buddhism]] in [[Japan]].
==History== Ancient [[Shinto shrine|shrines]] were constructed according to the style of dwellings ([[Izumo-taisha|Izumo Taisha]])<ref name="YY">Young & Young (2007:50)</ref><ref name="ki33">Kishida (2008:33)</ref> or storehouses ([[Ise Grand Shrine]]).<ref name="YY"/><ref name="fc">Fletcher and Cruickshank (1996:724)</ref> The buildings had [[:en:Gabled roof|Gabled roof]]s, raised floors, plank walls, and were [[thatching|thatched]] with reed or covered with [[Chamaecyparis obtusa|hinoki cypress]] bark.<ref name="fc"/> Such early shrines did not include a space for worship.<ref name="YY"/> Three important forms of ancient shrine architectural styles exist: ''[[taisha-zukuri]]'', ''[[shinmei-zukuri]]'', and ''sumiyoshi-zukuri''.<ref name="ki34">Kishida (2008:34)</ref> They are exemplified by [[Izumo-taisha|Izumo Taisha]], [[Nishina Shinmei Shrine]] and [[Sumiyoshi-taisha|Sumiyoshi Taisha]]<ref name="ki35">Kishida (2008:35)</ref> respectively and date to before 552.<ref name="ki126">Kishida (2008:126)</ref> According to the tradition of {{nihongo|''Shikinen sengū-sai|式年遷宮祭}}'', the buildings or shrines were faithfully rebuilt at regular intervals adhering to the original design. In this manner, ancient styles have been replicated through the centuries to the present day.<ref name="ki33"/>
==Structure== The ''honden'' on the grounds at Sumiyoshi Taisha has been designated as a [[National Treasures of Japan|national treasure]] on the grounds that it is the oldest example of this style of architecture. The four identical ''honden'' buildings that compose it are 4 ''ken'' wide and 2 ''ken'' deep and have an entrance under one of the [[:en:Gable|Gable]]s (a characteristic called {{nihongo|''[[tsumairi]]-zukuri''|妻入造}}. The roof is simple, doesn't curve upwards at the eaves and is decorated with purely ornamental poles called ''[[chigi (architecture)|chigi]]'' (vertical) and ''[[katsuogi]]'' (horizontal).<ref name="yahoo">[https://archive.today/20121209043808/http://100.yahoo.co.jp/detail/%E7%A5%9E%E7%A4%BE%E5%BB%BA%E7%AF%89/ Jinja Kenchiku], [[Shogakukan]] Nihon Daihyakka Zensho, accessed on November 29, 2009</ref> The building is surrounded by a fence called ''mizugaki'' (瑞垣), in its turn surrounded by another called {{nihongo|''[[tamagaki]]''|玉垣}} (see image in the gallery).<ref name="jasu"/> There is no veranda, and a short stairway leads to the door.
The interior is divided in two sections, one at the front ({{nihongo|''gejin''|外陣}}) and one at the back ({{nihongo|''naijin''|内陣}}) with a single entrance at the front (see floor plan in the gallery).<ref name="jasu">JAANUS, [http://www.aisf.or.jp/~jaanus/deta/s/sumiyoshizukuri.htm Sumiyoshi-zukuri], accessed on December 1, 2009</ref> The structure is simple, but brightly colored: supporting pillars are painted in vermilion and walls in white.
This style is supposed to have its origin in old palace architecture<ref name="jasu"/> Another example of this style is Sumiyoshi Jinja, part of the [[Sumiyoshi sanjin|Sumiyoshi Sanjin]] complex in [[Fukuoka Prefecture]].<ref name="jasu"/>
